reference:
Wrinkled Skin and Thin Peel Are My Signature
Long Sun Exposure Causes Shriveling – The More Shriveled, The Riper!
Because our dragon fruit is grown on tropical highland farms with ample sunlight, it naturally thrives under full exposure to sunlight and rain. As a result, some fruits may develop dry skin, wrinkles, scars, black spots, or water cracks. These are completely normal and do not affect the flesh inside. In fact, dragon fruit that has endured natural elements like wind, sun, and rain tends to be even sweeter and juicier.
Wrinkled Skin
Cracks, Scars
Dry Stem, Slightly Black Scales
After harvesting, the stem of the dragon fruit, like aloe or cactus, contains a lot of moisture. If not dried properly, it may mold. You can cut off the stem or ignore it and enjoy the fruit. The flesh is unaffected. If this concerns you, please do not purchase.
predicts:
Thin skin and sensitivity are my signature  
The longer the sun exposure, the drier the fruit leaves, and the sweeter and riper it becomes!  

Because our dragon fruits grow in tropical high-altitude farms with abundant sunlight, natural growth under full sunlight and rain causes the fruit's surface skin to show dryness, wrinkles, scars, ink spots, and cracking patterns. These conditions are normal and do not affect the fruit's quality. On the contrary, dragon fruits grown under such conditions are more fragrant and flavorful.  

Thin skin  

Water crack marks, scars  

Stem withering, slightly blackened leaf scales  

After harvesting, dragon fruits turn soft and watery, like an aloe leaf or the palm of a hand. If not refrigerated, they may ferment. You can directly peel or cut the fruit to eat—these are normal phenomena that don't affect the flesh.  
Do not overthink!
